TY  - JOUR
T1  - Expected Utility and the Truncated Normal Distribution
AU  - Norgaard, R.
AU  - Killeen, T.
Y1  - 1980/09/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.26.9.901
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.26.9.901
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 901
EP  - 909
VL  - 26
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This article demonstrates that: (1) When a normally distributed decision variable is combined with an analytic utility function (one with derivatives of all orders and a power series expansion involving those derivatives), the expected utility can be expressed in powers of ? and σ2. (2) In the case of the normal model, when the tails of the distribution do not reflect reality in the mind of a decision-maker, a truncated normal model is a possible alternative. (3) If the appropriate model is the truncated normal distribution, then the expected utility is approximately a linear function of ? and σ for several important classes of risk averse utility functions. (4) The negative exponential is an especially useful utility function since it has a simple closed form for both the truncated and nontruncated models, and since it gives an ordering similar to those of the log, arctangent or power utility functions.
AB  - This article demonstrates that: (1) When a normally distributed decision variable is combined with an analytic utility function (one with derivatives of all orders and a power series expansion involving those derivatives), the expected utility can be expressed in powers of ? and σ2. (2) In the case of the normal model, when the tails of the distribution do not reflect reality in the mind of a decision-maker, a truncated normal model is a possible alternative. (3) If the appropriate model is the truncated normal distribution, then the expected utility is approximately a linear function of ? and σ for several important classes of risk averse utility functions. (4) The negative exponential is an especially useful utility function since it has a simple closed form for both the truncated and nontruncated models, and since it gives an ordering similar to those of the log, arctangent or power utility functions.
